5000|$|The {{earliest}} {{reference to}} using herring for distracting hounds is {{an article published}} on 14 February 1807 by radical journalist William Cobbett in his polemical periodical Political Register. According to Cohen and Ross, and accepted by the OED, this is {{the origin of the}} figurative meaning of <b>red</b> <b>herring.</b> In the piece, William Cobbett critiques the English press, which had mistakenly reported Napoleon's defeat. Cobbett recounted that he had once used a <b>red</b> <b>herring</b> to deflect hounds in pursuit of a hare, adding [...] "It was a mere transitory effect of the political red-herring; for, on the Saturday, the scent became as cold as a stone." [...] Quinion concludes: [...] "This story, and Cobbett's extended repetition of it in 1833, was enough to get the figurative sense of <b>red</b> <b>herring</b> into the minds of his readers, unfortunately also with the false idea that it came from some real practice of huntsmen." ...|$|R
